Certainly not.  We deserve announcers who are knowledgeable about
the sport, and can communicate clearly, accurately, and with a
reasonable level of passion.  Football and basketball get that,
why should race fans settle for less?  We deserve color people who
add depth and insight to our understanding of what we see, not
ones who treat us like morons with first-grade level explanations.
Football and basketball get that, why should we settle for less?
We deserve on-screen graphics that convey meaningful information,
not &quot;technology for the sake of technology&quot; cluttering up the screen
and getting in the way of the event.  Football and basketball get
that, why should we settle for less?  We deserve production that
knows what happens on a race, and focuses on the action, not
bouncing all over the place for meaningless shots.  Football and
basketball get that, why should we settle for less?

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Racing is an extrememly difficult sport to capture on TV.  Anything
&gt; can happen at any moment on a &quot;playing field&quot; that can be over two
&gt; miles long.  There can be significant things happening literally a
&gt; mile apart and if you don't capture every bit of it all the time,
&gt; people say you suck.  It ain't fair.
">

It depends on why it wasn't captured.  If we're watching a battle
for 15th, and the leader blows a tire and hits the wall, and we
didn't see it live, then yeah, that's no fault of the director.

If we're watching Harvick battling Robby Gordon, and the director
switches to a shot of the leader running all by himself, and we
miss Harvick, etc, spinning, then we justly say the director sucks.
You, me, and everyone else in the NASCAR world know there's likely
to be action between certain drivers; and you, me, and everyone
else knows a shot of a car running by itself is just filler.

Again, I'll use football as the standard.  If we don't see the
blocked punt live because the shot switched to the return man
too soon, well that's unfortunate.  If we don't see the 50 yard
reception because the camera was focused on the running back,
then we'd call the director an idiot.  But that never happens.

John
