measure up here.  I'm not talkiing about who you just find irritating
to listen to.  Someone may not like the &quot;boogity, boogity, boogity&quot;,
but no thinking person would say that Darrell Waltrip doesn't know
what he's talking about.  Ditto for Rusty Wallace, Larry McReynolds,
Andy Petree, Jeff Hammond and Tim Brewer.  Mike Joy certainly knows
the sport as does Jerry Punch.

I'll grant that guys like Brent Musburger and Chris Myers might not
have as solid a background in racing as some of the other guys, but I
can't think of a single major player in the NA$CAr announcing game who
doesn't know what he's talking about or can't communicate clearly.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;  We deserve color people who
&gt; add depth and insight to our understanding of what we see, not
&gt; ones who treat us like morons with first-grade level explanations.
&gt; Football and basketball get that, why should we settle for less?
">

Maybe I'm just not as technically advanced as you are, but I have yet
to watch a race and feel like my intelligence has been insulted.  The
cutaway car segments are interesting to me and I can at least kinda
understand what's happening under the skin even though my knowledge of
race car mechanics would fit on the head of a pin.  The only thing I'd
classify as &quot;gadgetry&quot; is that thing that supposedly shows the clean
and dirty air.

I would note that racing is much more technically complex than any of
the stick and ball sports.  The announcers *have* to break it down
into relatively simple terms.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; We deserve on-screen graphics that convey meaningful information,
&gt; not &quot;technology for the sake of technology&quot; cluttering up the screen
&gt; and getting in the way of the event.
">

The crawl across the top of the screen giving the running order is no
more intrusive than the graphic at the top of the football telecasts
that shows the score, the clock and when there's a flag on the play.
The graphic showing the order off pit road is temporary and really
doesn't intrude on any action since they're still under caution.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; We deserve production that
&gt; knows what happens on a race, and focuses on the action, not
&gt; bouncing all over the place for meaningless shots.  Football and
&gt; basketball get that, why should we settle for less?
">

Football and basketball are played in a relatively compact space and
there's one primary point of focus--the ball.  Follow the ball and
you'll pretty much get everything that's essential to the game.

In racing there could be significant action taking place at the same
time literally a mile or more apart--and you never know when or where
something will happen.  Again, the nature of the sport puts the TV
crew in a no-win situation.  If you stay focused on the leaders, you
get criticized for ignoring the guys who may be putting on a good
show, but they're racing for 15th.  If you try to show some of the
other action, you get criticized for &quot;jumping around&quot; and ignoring
what's important.

My original point was simply that I think there are a bunch of fans
who don't really understand what the TV crews are up against trying to
capture everything that goes on during a race.  It's a tough sport to
do well.  If football is done better, it's because it a lot easier to
do.

The TV broadcasts aren't perfect and never will be, but I think that
overall, they do a dang good job given just how tough their job really
is.
