I know that I really dislike ESPN's coverage, and that it irks me in several
ways I've identified, and probably several I haven't.  Why I dislike it as
much as I do, I'm not sure, and it may be perceptual and a matter of taste.
Here's what I've figured out about why I don't like it.

1) Football promotion.  Breaking away to &quot;football update minutes&quot;, routing
(as last week) the conversation almost immediately during a red flag to
football rather than racing (no depth of knowledge there, Brad?),
continually promoting football broadcasts, the unspoken assumption that
we've turned the race on because what we really want is to *know the
football scores.*

Funny, I thought if what I really wanted was football, maybe I should go
find the Colts or Oklahoma game.  Matter of fact, that's what I do when I
want football.  And when I do, I'm not looking for the football commentators
to discuss Dale Earnhardt, Jr., either, or who's going to win the Chase.

When I turn on a race, I want to hear about racing.  Doesn't Fox, for
example, also promote other shows?  Yeah, they do, at least as much and
maybe more---this is probably one of those perceptual bits.  The types of
shows are all over the place (movies, sitcoms, what have you), and my brain
hears that as &quot;this is the stuff the network makes us promote&quot; and discards
it.  When ESPN guys do it, it seems to be 99% football, and my brain hears
often, &quot;God, this is what we'd rather be doing---as a network for sure, as
individuals maybe.  We only cover races because we gather they get an
audience, but we really can't understand WHY they get an audience.  We need
to convert you to football watchers instead.&quot;  And there's part of me that
perceives that that seems to come from the network more than from the
individual broadcasters---maybe with the exception of when Brad Daugherty
went off into football during the red flag this week.

2) The bottom of screen sports update crawl.  Once again, that seems to me
(perceptual again) to stress that ESPN doesn't consider races anything
special, and feels like races are just a time filler to them until the &quot;real
sports&quot; kick in.  **As a network**, they don't seem to really *get* anything
but &quot;classic&quot; (stick and ball, olympic) physical exertion based sports, and
racing doesn't fit that category.

Definitely in the personal and perceptual class is the aura of the
broadcasters: Fox and Speed definitely have a very laid-back aura, a &quot;we're
here to party with you and while we're at it, give you the benefit of our
expertise&quot; atmosphere.  TNT carries a good bit of that as well.  I happen to
like that sort of approach.

ESPN/ABC guys come across like they've been made to do this job wearing
underwear that's too tight, sitting on extremely uncomfortable chairs, with
the food and drink they've been denied since yesterday being just five
inches out of reach of the length of their mike cords: they range from
&quot;awfully businesslike or formal&quot; to &quot;uncomfortable being there&quot; (&quot;Is it over
yet? Can I take this mike off yet?&quot;) which may be partly an experience
issue: Rusty sounds more uncomfortable than some of the folks with a whole
lot less racing background.  Might be that nobody else sees/hears that;
might just be discomfort with their &quot;not-Fox-ness.&quot;  I dunno.

Anyhow, that's my personal analysis.

--pig
