&gt;because the baseball announcers assumed that their audience
&gt;was knowledgable in their sport, and thus didn't give a
&gt;first grade explanation of it).
">

OK.

If there are runners on first and second (or if the bases are
loaded), and there are less than two outs, an &quot;infield fly&quot; is called
if the batter pops the ball up in fair territory where an infielder
can easily catch it.  The batter is automatically out.  If the
infielder drops the ball, the runners can advance, but they don't have
to.

The idea behind it is to prevent an infielder from deliberately
dropping an easy pop-up, and then getting a double play (because the
runners would have to stay on their bases, since it looks like the
ball would be caught).

A good &quot;rule of thumb&quot;--if you could get a double play by letting
the ball drop instead of catching it, the infield fly rule is in
effect.

It's one of those &quot;unfair advantage&quot; rules like the ones that seem
to permeate NASCAR.

