&gt; because the baseball announcers assumed that their audience
&gt; was knowledgable in their sport, and thus didn't give a
&gt; first grade explanation of it).
">

The infield fly rule says that if there are runners on first and
second or the bases are loaded (IOW, there's a force out available at
third base) and less than two outs, the batter is automatically out if
he hits a fair fly ball that could reasonably be caught by an
infielder.  The idea is to prevent the defense from getting a cheap
double play.  Assume a pop-up to the third baseman.  The runners on
first and second are holding their bags expecting the ball to be
caught.  If the batter isn't automatically out, the third baseman can
intentionally let the ball drop, pick it up, touch third for a force
out, then throw to second for a second force out.  Calling the batter
out automatically removes the force plays and there is no advantage to
the defense to intentionally drop a ball that could easily be caught.
